<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="4300" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="4300">
<taxonomicName authority="Rafinesque-Schmaltz 1820" authorityYear="1820" class="Malacostraca" family="Asellidae" genus="Lirceus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lirceus fontinalis" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="4300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fontinalis">Lirceus fontinalis Rafinesque-Schmaltz 1820</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="4300" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="4300">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="4300">Patoka River NWR: 1, 3, 22, 25, 27, 29-31, 35, 36, 73, 79</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="4300">Muscatatuck NWR: 7-13, 16, 19, 20</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="4300">Big Oaks NWR: 13, 15, 20</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="4300">
The species ranges from southern Indiana, Kentucky, southwestern Ohio, and northern Tennessee (
<bibRefCitation author="Lewis, J. J." journalOrPublisher="Department of the Interior, U. S. Fish and Wildlife Service, Big Oaks National Wildlife Refuge, Madison, Indiana." pageId="0" pageNumber="4300" pagination="1 - 56" title="The subterranean fauna of the Big Oaks National Wildlife Refuge" volume="1" year="2002">Lewis and Rafail 2002</bibRefCitation>
). The bluegrass spring isopod was collected from caves in the Middle Fork, Big Creek, and Graham Creek watersheds.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="4300" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="4300">Ecology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="4300">
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Asellidae" genus="Lirceus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lirceus fontinalis" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="4300" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fontinalis">Lirceus fontinalis</taxonomicName>
(24%) was dominant within the refuges and is considered to have a wide habitat tolerance. The bluegrass spring isopod is a cave spring species associated with karst habitats (
<bibRefCitation author="Lewis, J. J." journalOrPublisher="Department of the Interior, U. S. Fish and Wildlife Service, Big Oaks National Wildlife Refuge, Madison, Indiana." pageId="0" pageNumber="4300" pagination="1 - 56" title="The subterranean fauna of the Big Oaks National Wildlife Refuge" volume="1" year="2002">Lewis and Rafail 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="4300" type="conservation">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="4300">Conservation</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="4300">The bluegrass spring isopod has a conservation species rank is S3/G4.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
